"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. I was talking with my auto mechanic Gilbert at Harold's uh autocare. Um he asked me how my business was doing, and I shared uh my business details with him, and you know, and I asked him how he was doing, he was steady eddy, you know, it's an auto mechanic, and uh I said, you know, you have a community-based business. They've been there a long time, they know their clients. Uh, and I was like, they trust you. You have your client's faith. Um, you actually have a community of people who need you and trust you because we don't know cars, we don't know trucks, you do. So we're trusting you, just almost like we trust doctors and stuff like that. We all need a good auto mechanic if we have cars. And he was like, Yeah, all my business is from existing clients. I don't do much with new stuff. He's like, couple percentage. I was like, wow, that's that's really something. And he had been there for years and years and years. I was like, you have a community, you need to keep that at all costs. Get that to the next generation, because a community-based business can survive the ups and downs. When things get lean, I still need my car fixed, I'm still gonna go to him. And that's what I'm trying to do with this gardener. I want to like root myself into the community, I want to get an income in the community, and so no matter what happens in this crazy world that falls apart economically, I have something that people want, and I can trade for it. You know, Bitcoin or dollars or gold or whatever the hell. Uh, but more than that, real currency is food. Food and water. That's what everyone needs all the time, no exceptions, no questions asked. Be a producer of that, and your future is set as far as you can do. All the other prepping is superfluous. Learn to make food, learn to collect water, the rest is gravy. Anyway, thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.16,\n      \"end\": 1.36,\n     